Change has been successfully rebased and submitted as 46b302837c3c44376da3ba6b72fb70b7b2ce1c11
First round of comments.
Please use the named "result" versions of these, unless you're doing 2XX level comparisons.  As written, I have to remember what 429 means 😊
Done
TODO: Do I need to explicitly copy over the return code?
Done

icompare, and needs to handle both forms of content-type.'

This is the perfect time to inform you that I'm adding a helper function that does this correctly for you 😊

If it does what you need, please just use it:
https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/bmcweb/+/59941/9/http/parsing.hpp#18

Thanks I can at least copy the same idea.  I don't think I want to call the function directly because it calls parse() and then discards the json.  I need to operate on the json so I'd have to call parse() again.
Disregard that, I see it returns the json as the second argument.  I can use it directly and should likely do the same for all of the processX() functions.

Actually I can't use it because it's designed for parsing requests and I need to parse a response.  Even if it could handle responses, it'd be a bit awkward to use in the short term.  We need to take 3 different actions depending on:
1) It's not an application/json
2) It's an application/json, but we failed to parse
3) It's an application/json and we parsed it

That helper function only has two exit routes until BMCWEB_INSECURE_IGNORE_CONTENT_TYPE is disabled by default.  Until then we'd have to derive if scenario 1) occurred.

I'm leaning towards copying the icompare portion for now.

Just to clarify, do we still need to do an icompare since we're parsing a response instead of a request?  It sounds like the issue being fixed by your linked patch is being caused by clients that are not in compliance with the spec.  We do not do case insensitive compares in the other locations where we are parsing a response for specific headers.
Shoot, missed this.  Sorry.  Yes, case-insensitive compares are required.  Technically the spec says that compares should be case insensitive.
I changed the Content-Type comparisons to use the same approach that you did in the linked file.
huh?  What form is this?
I've added additional clarification to the comment.
nit, log an error here?  if we're getting non-json-object responses from the satellite, it's arguably an error.
Logging an error is fair
Done
I've changed the code so that it can return early.  Please reopen if you have additional questions about the checks being made.
nit, another place you can save horizontal space.
ACK, I'll change that
I broke out some of the nested ifs

OH man.  This pattern has burned us so many times.  I get why you did it, but can you please be more specific about ONLY clearing the thing you expect to be there, rather than clearing the whole response?  Ideally we'd follow the design of never needing to delete, but that's a hard one in this case, and might need integrated with AsyncResp to do.

also, when you do this, I think this removes the need for the addedLinks variable, which seems to read as just a check to make sure you haven't cleared data that's already been posted.

The property I for sure want to remove is "error" if it exists.  My other concern (which I didn't articulate) is the local response may have been partially generated before throwing an error.  In that case I didn't want to expose any of that partial information since in the overall response it would not be possible to tell what properties came from a 200 response and what properties came from a partially populated non-200 response.

I've changed the code to only clear "error" and leave whatever properties may have been populated before the error occurred.  We need the addedLinks boolean because we do not want to remove errors from a non-200 local response unless one of the satellite responses contains a valid link that we want to add.

I've also added additional test cases to verify this behavior.
ACK, I'll fix that
Done although I had to create a new iterator each time because it had to be const.

I don't think this is an error in all cases, for example, the AdditionalDataUri property?  I'm ok with not handling it for now, but lets leave a comment for now that this is incorrect and needs fixed.

I think it would be in the sense that we are only parsing responses from URIs which are uptree from top level collections.  If something like /redfish/v1 or /redfish/v1/UpdateService on a satellite did not return a json then the aggregator can't do anything with it anyway.

AdditionalDataURI should appear under a resource which is part of a top level collection so it should never show up when parsing a response as part of processContainsSubordinateResponse().
Ack
There's more valid responses than this?

200 is really the only valid response for this.  However, 429 and 502 are dummy responses generated by the aggregated when we didn't successfully forward the responses because either the request buffer was full so we dropped the request (429) or we exhausted the retry policy (502).

This also matches the handling we use for processCollectionResponse().  There is a lot of similarity in how we process collection responses and responses that are uptree from a top level collection.

In both instances it may be fine to just simplify it to !200.
I removed the additional checks for 429 and 502 at the end of the processX() functions.  They shouldn't be needed since there is also a check at the start of those functions for these response codes.
whether it is required to add failure msg incase this if block is failed

I don't think so.  The satellite should include these properties, but at no point in aggregation do we take special actions like dropping the response if those properties do not exist.  

One of these checks failing would be surfaced anyway in the overall response when that property is missing.
